Introduction
"Please!", pleaded Queen Eirwen. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The King of Ice looked at his wife from the top of his throne, his royal advisor beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. He scowled at the thought.
The little girl looked a lot like her mother: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue locks. The Ice King thought a daughter would make him look weak. After all, he had only sons so far.
"Your only options are to kill your child or send it back to nature. That's its punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did.
Frostwell was not always a single kingdom. It had been divided in two, North and South. To the north, the non-magical kingdom. To the south, a kingdom filled with fantastical representations of power. Due to the greed of the North, the two kingdoms had torn themselves apart in an endless war, until the South proposed a truce.
The South was cornered, and its royal family would have done anything to stop the bloodbath. They proposed that their only princess become the queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Then, the South would have allied itself with the North to form a single kingdom. The North had accepted, and Princess Eirwen had married Prince Akull.
"Please, my highness, in exchange for the life of my child, do with me as you wish, lock me up, banish me, or even kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child tightly in her arms.
The King of Ice looked down at his wife, disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he would pity her. The one with whom he had lived for twenty-two years, who had always taken care of him, in his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Very well, the child will live in the palace", he began, drawing a sigh of relief from his wife. "However", he added, "you will be executed".
The advisor and Queen Eirwen herself shared a horrified glance. She lowered her gaze slowly. "Yes, Your Highness", she said, bowing.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to take the child to one of the vacant rooms in Eirwen. Once this was done, he commanded the guards to bring Eirwen to the execution site, where all the villagers could attend the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, residents shouted in indignation at the sight of their only queen, the kindest of them all, on the verge of being killed. Some people were crying, others were screaming and trying to attack the guards, while others still were wondering what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Set her free!"
"Why are they doing this to him?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom entered. The Fire User. Former Queen Eirwen was to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even the criminals. It was the cruelest punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was hanged from the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then the fire user set the gallows ablaze, and a single tear rolled down the cheek of the former queen.
Survived, Kari. This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds coming from the farthest room to the left of the frozen palace wing. Servants passing by always wondered what was inside, frightened by what might be within. The maids' rumors danced through the corridors. It was believed that the late queen of Glace's wife, Eirwen, was in this room, waiting to be freed.
"They couldn't possibly be more wrong", Ivory thought as she walked towards the southern wing, while the aides came and went, murmuring to each other. They have no idea what's in this room.
Of course, these rumors also applied to him, as he was the only person authorized to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Miss Kari, are you there?", whispered Ivory to the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
She wondered if she would invite him in, unlike the other times when he had asked her. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory chuckled at this memory. Kari had thrown a book over his shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
Just one knock came from inside, which seemed to mean she was there, but then again, where else would she have been?
"Can I come in?", Ivory asked, remembering the time he had done it without asking for permission.
A knock resounded from inside. It seemed as if it wanted to say yes. Ivory shuddered, with cold, but also due to the noise. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a room supposed to be empty, even though she had entered this room for years.
"I'm here," said Ivory, gently opening the door. The scene inside the room was unusual, by normal people's standards, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken and a multitude of ice trophies were scattered. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was also colder in there than anywhere else in the palace (and that wasn't saying much). A snowstorm seemed to have hit inside.
The girl who was there was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her quilt, where she was reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the space.
"What notebook is this?", Ivory asked, sitting down beside Kari on her bed.
